<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-27T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-27T19:00:00-05:00" n="207" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d207">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Tientsin/229: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul General at Tientsin</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-27T19:00:00-05:00">March 27, 1939—7
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>15. Your 43, March 23, 6 p.m. Bearing in mind the considerations
                                outlined in the first paragraph of the Department’s 110, December
                                15, 4 p.m.,<note n="54" xml:id="d207fn54"><ref target="frus1938v04#pg_103"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, 1938, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>,
                                        p. 103</ref>.</note> you may notify the Japanese Consul
                                General of the number of Americans residing in Tientsin and of the
                                number of passes that will be needed.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Peiping and Chungking.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>